For myself, after a good deal of patient investigation be- stowed upon the derivation of the place-names of the district, Ι have no doubt that the first element in the name is what so large a majority of the prefixes in our local nomenclature clearly are, and that is the name of a person. Such a name existed in the eleventh century, in the form of an agnomen or nickname—Mr. Freeman calls it a surname—in the case of Edric Streone, and we find it as a prefix in the name Streon- bercht, which occurs in the Liber Vitae. But as to the meaning of the suffix, that is clearly uncertain.
